      "title": "Module 1: Map your triggers before they arrive",
      "text": "A trigger is just an old association — a moment your brain learned to pair with smoking. The morning coffee, the after-meal pause, the phone call, the drive, the drink, the work break, a particular person. In the first couple of weeks these moments will still fire the old \"time for a cigarette\" signal, like flicking the indicator and getting the windscreen wipers in a new car. It's harmless and temporary — the wiring just needs a short while to update. But it's far easier to handle a trigger you expected than one that ambushes you.\n\nSo today you'll list your top triggers and decide, in advance, exactly what you'll do at each one. This is the most evidence-backed planning tool in behavioural psychology: the implementation intention, or \"if–then\" plan. People who pre-decide \"if X happens, then I'll do Y\" follow through far more often than people who simply intend to \"stay strong.\""
